******
[2]
Date: Mon 11 Jul 2011
Source: The Australian [edited]
http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/interstate-taskforce-set-up-to-contain-hendra/story-e6frg6nf-1226091922081


New South Wales [NSW] and Queensland have stepped up cooperation to
contain the biggest outbreak of Hendra disease on record as properties
on both side of the border remain locked down. The premiers of each
state, having discussed the emergency, agreed yesterday [10 Jul 2011]
to set up a joint taskforce to deliver what Anna Bligh [Premier of
Queensland] called a "consistent and coordinated" approach.

Two horses are dead in NSW in the 1st eruptions of the disease there
for 5 years, and 5 more have died in Queensland over the past
fortnight after 3 separate outbreaks in that state.

Ominously, the incident in NSW at Macksville, south of Coffs Harbour,
is the farthest south Hendra has been detected. A 16-year-old mare
died there last Sunday [3 Jul 2011], and 6 people are being monitored
in case of a crossover infection.

In Queensland, 17 people are yet to receive the all-clear after being
exposed to the bat-borne virus in outbreaks at Beaudesert, Mount
Alford, and Park Ridge, all southwest of Brisbane.

Scientists have speculated that last summer's [2010-11] disastrous
floods in Queensland and in northern NSW might have reduced the food
supply of fruit bats, increasing stress levels that cause them to
express the lethal virus. All 4 species of Australian flying fox carry
Hendra, but researchers say they cannot fully explain how it is passed
to horses and, in some cases, on to people.

The best explanation is that horses are infected by the contamination
of feed or pasture from bat droppings and bodily secretions.

People who come into close contact with diseased horses -- typically
their handlers and vets -- are then put at risk.

The Queensland Premier said closer cooperation between the states was
important to understanding this latest outbreak.

Ms Bligh said more than 40 horses were under quarantine in
Queensland, on 9 properties, and were being checked daily for signs of
disease. In all, 32 people in both states were being monitored. But
none was considered to be sufficiently exposed to warrant treatment
with an experimental anti-serum that can stop progression of the
disease.

[Byline: Jamie Walker ]

